I have everything I need. Here is the full review.

---

## Simplification Opportunities

### 1. Duplicate storage list scan in `scheduleNextAlarm`

**`apps/cloud-relay/src/relay-do.ts`, lines 593–601**

`scheduleNextAlarm` calls `ctx.storage.list({ prefix: "pending:" })` and then immediately calls `ctx.storage.list({ prefix: "pending:pair:" })`. The second call is a strict subset of the first — `pending:pair:*` entries are already returned by the `pending:` prefix scan. The first loop on lines 594–596 already pushes every entry (including pair entries) into `candidates`, so the second loop is redundant and costs a second storage round-trip on every alarm invocation. The `pending:pair:` entries do need to be excluded from client deadline consideration (which `getPendingClients` correctly handles), but for the purpose of collecting deadline timestamps into `candidates`, a single `pending:` scan is sufficient.

### 2. `getPendingClients` and the alarm both list `pending:` separately

**`apps/cloud-relay/src/relay-do.ts`, lines 243, 593**

`alarm()` calls `getPendingClients()` (which issues a `list({ prefix: "pending:" })` at line 621) and then `scheduleNextAlarm()` which issues another `list({ prefix: "pending:" })` at line 593. Those are two storage round-trips that scan the same key space back-to-back within a single alarm invocation. The results from `getPendingClients()` could be passed into `scheduleNextAlarm` as a parameter, eliminating the second scan.

### 3. `webSocketClose` and `webSocketError` are identical

**`apps/cloud-relay/src/relay-do.ts`, lines 196–235**

The bodies of `webSocketClose` (lines 202–216) and `webSocketError` (lines 219–234) are character-for-character identical. Both extract tags, check for `"tunnel"` / `"pairer"` / `"client"`, and dispatch to the same handlers. One could delegate to the other, or both could call a shared private `handleWebSocketTermination(ws)` method, cutting ~20 lines of duplication.

### 4. Inconsistent URL construction in the proxy routes

**`apps/cloud-relay/src/index.ts`, lines 47–74**

Three of the four routes (tunnel, connect, pair) construct a new URL by mutating `pathname` on a parsed copy of `c.req.url` and then pass `new Request(newUrl, c.req.raw)` to forward the original request with its headers and upgrade semantics. The fourth route (`/status`, line 71–74) constructs its URL differently: `new URL("/status", c.req.url)` — this is correct but the construction method is inconsistent with the pattern above. More importantly, `/status` is the only route that does NOT forward `c.req.raw` — it passes a plain `new Request(...)` with no headers. For a non-WebSocket, non-authenticated endpoint that is fine, but the inconsistency will confuse readers. All four routes could use the same URL-mutation pattern for clarity.

### 5. `pair_response` success-branch uses runtime `"in"` guard instead of the discriminated type

**`apps/cloud-relay/src/relay-do.ts`, lines 310–313**

```ts
if (frame.success && "deviceToken" in frame) {
  this.safeSend(pairerWs, { type: "pair_success", token: frame.deviceToken });
} else {
  const reason = "reason" in frame ? frame.reason : "Pairing failed";
```

`ServerFrame` already carries this as a proper discriminated union on `success: true | false` (defined in `shared/types/relay.ts` lines 13–14). After Zod validation the cast at line 179 ensures the type is `ServerFrame`. Narrowing via `frame.success === true` is sufficient — the `"deviceToken" in frame` and `"reason" in frame` guards are unnecessary given the discriminated union is already resolved. The fallback `"Pairing failed"` string can also never be reached because `pair_response` with `success: false` always has a `reason` field in the type definition.

### 6. `findClientWs` and `findPairerWs` are near-identical

**`apps/cloud-relay/src/relay-do.ts`, lines 630–646**

```ts
private findClientWs(clientId: string): WebSocket | null {
  const allClients = this.ctx.getWebSockets("client");
  for (const ws of allClients) {
    const tags = this.ctx.getTags(ws);
    if (tags.includes(clientId)) return ws;
  }
  return null;
}

private findPairerWs(pairId: string): WebSocket | null {
  const allPairers = this.ctx.getWebSockets("pairer");
  for (const ws of allPairers) {
    const tags = this.ctx.getTags(ws);
    if (tags.includes(pairId)) return ws;
  }
  return null;
}
```

These are structurally identical modulo the tag group (`"client"` vs `"pairer"`) and the ID parameter name. A single private `findWs(group: string, id: string): WebSocket | null` would replace both.

### 7. `pairId` extraction repeated in three dispatch sites

**`apps/cloud-relay/src/relay-do.ts`, lines 181, 208–209, 224–225**

The pattern `tags.find((t) => t !== "pairer")` to extract the `pairId` from tags appears in `webSocketMessage`, `webSocketClose`, and `webSocketError`. The same pattern for `clientId` (replacing `"pairer"` with `"client"`) appears three more times. This could be extracted to a small helper `getIdFromTags(tags, group)` that returns the second tag element, since the tag arrays are always two elements: `[group, id]`.

### 8. `RelayPairerFrame` and `PairerFrame` are unnecessary aliases

**`shared/types/relay.ts`, lines 57–58**

```ts
export type PairerFrame = PairerRequestFrame;
export type RelayPairerFrame = PairerResponseFrame;
```

These are pure re-exports of types defined 10 lines above in the same file. The import in `relay-do.ts` (line 20) could use `PairerRequestFrame` and `PairerResponseFrame` directly, removing the alias indirection entirely. The current names (`PairerFrame`, `RelayPairerFrame`) also break the naming convention established by the other pairs (`ServerFrame`/`RelayFrame`, `ClientAuthFrame`/`RelayClientFrame`) — `PairerRequestFrame`/`PairerResponseFrame` are already the more descriptive names.

### 9. `server_offline` type in `RelayClientFrame` is never emitted

**`shared/types/relay.ts`, line 36**

```ts
| { type: "server_offline"; serverName: string | null; serverDisconnectedAt: number }
```

`relay-do.ts` only ever emits `server_reconnecting` (lines 379, 477, 559). `server_offline` appears in the type definition but there is no emit site for it in the relay code. If it is used by a consuming client, it is a dead variant that adds type-union noise. If it is not used anywhere, it can be removed.

### 10. `MockWebSocketPair` has numeric index properties but is only accessed via `Object.values()`

